{"title_page": "Khokhar Khanzada", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Shameel Khokhar\n|image         = \n|office        =  [[DRSM Library QAU Islamabad]]\n|term_start    = 1st January 2017\n|term_end      = \n|primeminister = [[Imran Khan]]\n|predecessor   = [[Arif Alvi]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = Member of the [[Computer Printing DRSM Library QAU Islamabad]]\n|term_start1   = 1 January 2017\n|term_end1     = \n|constituency1 = [[45320 (Quaid-i-Azam University Islamabad)]]\n|successor1 = [[Imran Khan]] \n|predecessor1 = Himself\n|term_start2   = \t\n|term_end2     =  \n|constituency2 = \n|successor2 = Himself\n|predecessor2  = \n|birth_date    =  {{Birth date and age|1997|12|06|df=y}} \n|birth_place   = [[Jhelum]], [[Punjab Province (1997-22)|Pakistan]], [[Dominion of Pakistan|Pakistan]]\n|nationality   = Pakistani\n|party         =  [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n|spouse        = \n|children      = No\n|residence     = [[D-Type Colony Quaid-i-Azam University]], [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Allama Iqbal Open University Islamabad, Pakistan]]\n}}\n\n'''Shameel Khokhar''' ({{Lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0634\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u0644 \u06a9\u06be\u0648\u06a9\u06be\u0631}}}}; born 06 December 1997)  is a Pakistani.\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group|\n|group= Khokhar Khanzada\n|popplace = \u2022 {{flagcountry|India}}\n|langs = \u2022 [[Urdu language|Urdu]] \u2022 [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n|rels= \u2022 [[File:Allah-green.svg|18px]] [[Islam]] 100% \u2022\n|related= \u2022 [[Khokhar]] \u2022  [[Khanzada (Awadh)|Khanzada]] \u2022 [[Punjabi Jat]] .\n}}\n\nThe '''Khokhar Khanzada''' are \nmuslim community found mainly in the [[Fatehpur district]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] in [[India]]. They have no connection with the [[Ranghar]] [[Khokhar]] of [[Moradabad district]] in western [[Uttar Pradesh]], another community of [[Muslim]] [[Khokhar]]s settled in [[Uttar Pradesh]]. The [[Khokhar]] are a well known tribe, found mainly in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] region of [[Pakistan]] and [[India]]. The Khokhar Khanzada are a sub-community within the larger [[Khanzada (Awadh)|Khanzada]] community of eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>Fatehpur District : A Gazetteer Volume XX, District Gazetteers of the United Provinces edited by H Neville</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe Khokhar Pathan claim descent from Malik Babur, who said to have come from [[Kapurthala|kabool]] & Iran He was sent to [[Fatehpur district|Fatehpur]] by the [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] authorities in [[Delhi]] to suppress the [[Bhar]]s, a tribe that controlled most of eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]]. The [[Malik]] successfully defeated the [[Bhar]]s, and the grateful [[Alauddin Khalji]], the [[Delhi Sultanate|Sultan of Delhi]] granted several villages as a  [[jagir]] (estate) in [[Fatehpur district]], the main one being [[Kot, Fatehpur|Kot, shivpuri, manmai]]. In addition to the settlement at [[Kot, Fatehpur|Kot]], they are also found in the villages of Arhaiya, Urha, Shahnagar, Rahmatpur, Shivpuri, Kulli, Ghazipur and Parvezpur. Other than the [[jagirdar]] families, the majority of the [[Fatehpur district|Fatehpur]] Khokhar are small to medium-sized farmers. With the abolishment of [[zamindar]]i system of feudal ownership by the Indian government in 1949, this has had a strong impact on the large landowning families, as much of their land has been redistributed. A further change has been that many Khokhar Khanzada have also emigrated to [[Pakistan]], and are now found mainly in [[Karachi]].\n\n==Customs and Traditions==\nThey are [[Shia|Shias]] [[Muslim]]s,  and have customs similar to other [[Khanzada (Awadh)|Khanzada]] communities in the region. The community is largely endogamous, although there are cases of intermarriage with the [[Gautam Khanzada]], a neighbouring [[Muslim Rajput]] population. But most marriages are with a close kin, with the community practicing both parallel cousin and cross cousin marriages. The community speak [[Urdu]], as well as the [[Awadhi]] dialect.<ref>Fatehpur District : A Gazetteer Volume XX, District Gazetteers of the United Provinces edited by H Neville</ref>\n\n==Khokhar Ranghar==\nThe town of [[Sambhal]] in [[Moradabad District]] is also home to several families of [[Khokhar]]s, who have said to have emigrated from [[Gujrat District|Gujrat]] in what is now [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Pakistani Punjab]] during the reign of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] Emperor [[Babur|Babar]]. As most [[Rajput]] converts to [[Islam]] were in common parlance referred to as [[Ranghar]], these [[Khokhar]]s were also referred to as the Khokhar. The Emperor Babar himself is said to have granted the Khokhars [[jagir]] for the town of the [[Sambhal]]. They played a particularly important role in [[Rohilkhand]] politics during the period of [[Rohilla]] rule. The Khokhar were the effective rulers of the town of [[Sambhal]] and the adjoining countryside until the establishment of [[United Kingdom|British]] rule after the [[Rohilla War]] of 1774. Although the Khokhars lost independent power, they remained one of the larger landowners in the district till 1949, when the newly independent [[India]] carried out substantive land reform, and broke up the large estates. The Khokhars remain a substantial element in the population of [[Sambhal]].<ref>Moradabad District United Provinces District Gazetteers edited by H Neville</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Khokhar]]\n* [[Khanzada (Awadh)|Khanzada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Indian Muslim}}\n{{Muhajir communities}}\n\n[[Category:Khanzada]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n", "name_user": "Kinginsin", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khokhar_Khanzada"}
{"title_page": "List of CBRN warfare forces", "text_new": "Several countries around the world maintain military units that are specifically trained to cope with CBRN (Chemical, Biological, Radiological, Nuclear) threats. Beside this specialized units, most modern armed forces undergo generalized basic CBRN self-defense training for all their personnel. \n\n{{TOC right}}\n==Albania==\n* Central Laboratory of the Armed Forces \u2013 Military Unit Nr.4010 ('' Laboratori Qendror i Forcave t\u00eb Armatosura - Rep. Usht. Nr.4010'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaf.mil.al/index.php/brigada-logjistike/159-struktura/4356-laboratori-qendror-i-forcave-te-armatosura-rep-usht-nr-4010|title=Laboratori Qendror i Forcave t\u00eb Armatosura Rep. Usht. Nr.4010|website=aaf.mil.al|date=|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Argentina==\n* 601st Chemical Biological Nuclear and Emergency Support Engineers Company (''Compa\u00f1\u00eda de Ingenieros de Defensa Quimica Bacteriologica Nuclear y Apoyo a la Emergencia 601'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/el-ministerio-de-defensa-visito-la-compania-de-ingenieros-de-defensa-qbn-y-apoyo-la|title=El Ministerio de Defensa visit\u00f3 la Compa\u00f1\u00eda de Ingenieros de Defensa QBN y Apoyo a la Emergencia 601, para informarse acerca del equipamiento y las capacidades de esta subunidad especial|website=argentina.gob.ar|date=16 May 2019|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\n* Special Operations Engineer Regiment<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.gov.au/our-people/units/special-operations-command/special-operations-engineer-regiment|title=Special Operations Engineer Regiment|website=army.gov.au|date=|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Austria==\n* Atomic, Biological, Chemical \u2013 Defense School \u201cLise Meitner\u201d (''Atomar, Biologisch, Chemisch-Abwehrschule \u201cLise Meitner\u201d'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesheer.at/cms/artikel.php?ID=3351|title=ABC-Abwehrschule feiert neuen Traditio