ll]]\n|artists             = [[Gabriel Rodriguez (artist)|Gabriel Rodr\u00edguez]]\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           = [[Robbie Robbins]]\n|colorists           = [[Jay Fotos]]\n|editors             = [[Chris Ryall]]\n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            = \n|TPB1                = Welcome to Lovecraft\n|ISBN1               = 9781600102370\n|TPB2                = Head Games\n|ISBN2               = 9781600104831\n|TPB3                = Crown of Shadows\n|ISBN3               = 9781600106958\n|TPB4                = Keys to the Kingdom\n|ISBN4               = 9781600108860\n|TPB5                = Clockworks\n|ISBN5               = 9781613772270\n|TPB6                = Alpha & Omega\n|ISBN6               = 9781613778531\n|subcat              = IDW Publishing <!-- doesn't seem to work, hence the addpubcat1 -->\n|altcat              =\n|alttop              =\n|sort                = Locke &amp; Key\n|addpubcat1          = IDW Publishing titles\n}}\n'''''Locke & Key''''' is an American [[comic book]] series written by [[Joe Hill (writer)|Joe Hill]], illustrated by [[Gabriel Rodriguez (artist)|Gabriel Rodr\u00edguez]], and published by [[IDW Publishing]].\n\n==Plot summary==\n\nThis plot is presented in chronological order. During the [[American Revolution]], a group of Rebels, hiding beneath the future Keyhouse, discover a portal to another dimension, the [[Leng (plateau)|plains of Leng]] filled with demons who can mesmerize anyone that sees them and possess them through touch. However, when the demons attempt to enter the real world, they transformed into \"whispering\" iron which young smith Benjamin Locke forged into a variety of magical keys, including the Omega Key, which seals the entrance to the dimension. The magic of the Keyhouse gradually evolves over the years, including a spell which causes occupants to forget about the keys and the magic of the house when they pass their 18th birthday. In 1988, a group of teenagers, having used the keys extensively in their high school years to their great delight, decide to open the black door with the Omega Key, hoping to trick a demon into entering the real world in order to provide more metal with which to make more keys. Rendell Locke's younger brother follows the group and is mesmerized by the door and when attempting to walk through it, he is stopped by Dodge who accidentally puts his hand through the door, becoming possessed. After plotting and attempting to kill his friends and enslave the others at the behest of the Child of Leng possessing him, Dodge is killed by Rendell.\n\nMany years later, Dodge's spirit re-enters the physical world through the well at Keyhouse, due to actions taken by Dodge prior to his death. Trapped in the well, Dodge's spirit reaches out to a young abused prodigy, Sam Lesser, and convinces him to attack the Lockes and kill Rendell, looking for the Omega Key, as well as the Anywhere Key, which is capable of freeing Dodge from the well. After the gruesome murder of their father, the Locke kids, Tyler, Kinsey, and Bode move with their mother Nina across the country to Keyhouse and begin discovering its secrets. Sam escapes prison and follows the Lockes to Massachusetts. He attacks the family again at Keyhouse, at which time Dodge tricks Bode into bringing him the Anywhere Key. Dodge escapes from the well, kills Sam and returns to Lovecraft in the same body as he had thirty years before.\n\nDodge re-enters high school under the guise of a new student, intimidating his way into the home of one of Kinsey's teachers and Dodge's former friends. Over the next year, Dodge secretly tries to recover the various keys - in particular the Omega Key - from the children, collecting many, though hindered by Tyler and Kinsey. Dodge is eventually discovered but manages to switch bodies and possess Bode before they can kill him. Now free to explore the house as Bode, Dodge finally finds the Omega Key and plans his takeover after-prom party in the caves. He releases several demons and many of the students are killed. Dodge is ultimately undone by Tyler and Dodge's spirit is forced back into the well, though Bode's empty body is cremated before Bode's soul has a chance to return to it. In the epilogue, Tyler returns to the well to finally free Dodge's spirit from the demon, having used a sliver of whispering iron inherited from his father to forge an \"Alpha Key\" capable of undoing possession. Tyler is able to speak with his father one last time, and he restores Bode's physical form.\n\n==Publication history==\nThe narrative of ''Locke & Key'' has a three-act structure, with each act covering two story arcs. Act One's first [[story arc]], ''Welcome to Lovecraft'', was a six-issue [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] published by [[IDW Publishing]]. The first issue of ''Welcome to Lovecraft'' was released on February 20, 2008, and sold out in a single day, requiring a second printing to be done immediately.<ref>{{cite web| last = Powers| first = Kevin| title = Fantasy-Horror Comic Locke & Key Sold Out in One Day| publisher = [[Comics Bulletin]]| date = 2008-02-21| url = http://www.comicsbulletin.com/news/120365512436828.htm| accessdate = 2008-12-09}}</ref> The second arc of Act One, ''Head Games'', commenced with the release of the first issue on January 22, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title = Joe Hill talks Locke & Key: Head Games | publisher = [[Comic Book Resources]]| date = 2009-01-12 | url = http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=19506 | accessdate = 2009-02-27}}</ref> The actual ''Head Games'' story was printed in four issues, with a standalone prologue (\"Intermission\" or \"The Joe Ridgeway Story\") and a standalone conclusion (\"Army of One\").<ref name=\"sorta\">{{cite web| last = Hill | first = Joe | authorlink = Joe Hill (writer) | title = Be at Peace | work = Joe Hill Fiction | date = 2009-06-01 | url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=906 | accessdate = 2009-06-01 | quote = Sorta, not quite. HEAD GAMES is actually four-issues long, with a standalone prologue (\u201dIntermission\u201d or \u201cThe Joe Ridgeway Story\u201d) and a standalone conclusion (\u201dArmy of One\u201d).}}</ref>\n\nThe first storyline of ''Locke & Key'' Act Two, ''Crown of Shadows'', began in late 2009.<ref>{{cite web| last = Hill | first = Joe | title = Be at Peace | work = Joe Hill Fiction | date = 2009-06-01 | url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=906 | accessdate = 2009-06-01 | quote = I wasn\u2019t asked, but I\u2019ll say at this point the plan is for four more six-issue LOCKE & KEY stories, the next being CROWN OF SHADOWS in the fall/winter of this year.}}</ref> The second storyline, ''Keys to the Kingdom'', began in August 2010.\n\nThe first storyline of Act Three was announced as ''Time & Tide'',<ref>{{cite web| title = LOCKE & KEY Comics Head to a Close, Door Opens for TV Series | publisher = [[Newsarama]]| date = 2010-09-24 | url = http://www.newsarama.com/comics/locke-and-key-joe-hill-100924.html | accessdate = 2010-11-23}}</ref> but was retitled ''Clockworks''.<ref>{{cite web| title = Feast Your Eyes | publisher = Joe Hill Fiction | date = 2010-01-24 | url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=1737 | accessdate = 2010-01-30}}</ref> The second, and concluding, storyline is entitled ''Alpha & Omega''.\n\nOriginally, the plan was to release the first five story arcs the monthly format with the sixth arc published as an [[graphic novel|original graphic novel]]. The plan changed and the concluding story arc appeared in monthly installments.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Serwin| first = Andy|date=March 2009| title = Up Close: Joe Hill (interview)| journal = [[Wizard (magazine)|Wizard]]| volume = 1| issue = 209| pages = 22| publisher = [[Wizard Entertainment]]| location = [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury, CT]]| issn = 1065-6499| quote = In a weird way, ''Welcome to Lovecraft'' was really the prologue. It was the two-hour pilot, and now the TV series is beginning for real. There's gonna be 24 issues. We're gonna go for two years, and then there's gonna be a break, and then there'll be a final graphic novel to wrap things up. If you look at it broadly, it has a bit of a three-act structure, so the first 12 issues are one act\u2026 something happens at the end of issue #12 which begins to change things. The next 12 issues are Act 2, and then that final graphic novel will be Act 3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://joehillfiction.informe.com/forum/locke-key-f15/what-happens-after-6-t907.html#p21890 | title = Re: What happens after #6? | accessdate = December 9, 2008 | last = Rodriguez | first = Gabriel | date = 2008-07-29 | work = The Joe Hill Message Board | quote = [\u2026]but starting this winter, you'll have 24 L&K issues MONTHLY, two years of uninterrupted series, and then a little pause before the grand finale graphic novel!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Hill | first = Joe | authorlink = Joe Hill (writer) | title = Be at Peace | work = Joe Hill Fiction | date = 2009-06-01 | url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=906 | accessdate = 2009-06-01 | quote = I had thought at one point we might go monthly, but now I think it might be wiser to do it in six-issue bites. [\u2026] Also, a plan to end the series with a standalone graphic novel has been scrapped. I\u2019d rather go with individual issues: for me, crafting the story in discreet 22-page portions is the great pleasure of the thing, and I don\u2019t want to abandon what\u2019s working.}}</ref>\n\n==Keys==\n\nIn the universe of ''Locke & Key'', there are many keys created from whispering iron that have different magical properties. Some of them are extensively featured in the series, while others are featured very briefly. The known keys are:\n\n* '''Age Key''': Can turn the bearer into an older version of themself, possibly other ages.\n* '''Alpha Key''': Removes demons from possessed people's souls when inserted into their chests. It instantly turns a demon to whispering iron, so if it is still inside the host, it is fatal.\n* '''Angel Key''': Inserted into a harness with large feathered wings, it grants a person the power of winged flight.\n* '''Animal Key''': Used on the right door in Keyhouse, it allows the user to travel through the door and transform into an animal. (It is unclear whether they have choice in the matter. It appears that the key assigns the animal, according to some spiritual affinity.) Returning back through the door transforms a person back into a human. This works for human ghosts that have possessed animal bodies. Animals may also transform into humans if they enter through the opposite side of the door.\n* '''Anywhere Key''': Opens a door to anywhere the bearer can visualize in their mind.\n* '''Chain Key''': Controls the Great Lock, which guards the catacombs with entangling chains.\n* '''Echo Key''': Allows entry to the Keyhouse well house and, with the Echo Key in hand, allows a person to return a spirit from the dead to the world of the living. Leaving through the well house door, however, banishes the spirit back to wherever it came from.\n* '''Gender Key''': Unlocks a half-sized door between rooms which changes the sex of a person who enters it.\n* '''Ghost Key''': When used in the right door in Keyhouse, it separates the soul from the body of whoever travels through the door. The body falls dead while their ghost is free to roam the Keyhouse grounds. Ghost souls can inhabit any other bodies nearby, and clash with other ghosts.\n* '''Giant Key''': This physically large key, once inserted into a keyhole-shaped window in Keyhouse, transforms the bearer into a massive giant.\n* '''Grindhouse Key''': Transforms whatever door it opens into a giant mouth that consumes whatever enters it.\n* '''Harlequin Key''': Unlocks the Harlequin Wardrobe and allows objects not normally inside to be seen.\n* '''Head Key''': Inserted into the base of someone's head, it allows one to peer inside the mind of a person, where memories and mental concepts (including \"sanity\" itself) are represented as tiny beings. The memories can be removed, and swapped between people. Books inserted into a head with the Head Key transfer their contents to the bearer of the key, though in such a situation the knowledge of the text is accurate but superficial.\n* '''Hell Key''': The bearer is automatically the Lord of Hell and has absolute control over Hell.\n* '''Hercules Key''': Embedded in a necklace, it grants the bearer considerable strength and bulk.\n* '''Identity Key''': Upon inserting into the base of one's chin, the bearer can change any aspect of their appearance, including clothes, body, or even gender. Also allows a bearer to forcibly change the appearance of others.\n* '''Jester Key''': Opens a magical cabinet in Keyhouse that contains a number of artifacts and keys.\n* '''Keyhouse Key''': A large key which fits into a stone slab and regenerates the Keyhouse after it is destroyed.\n* '''Matchstick Key''': Creates fires when inserted into a door or touched to an object. Can also cause self-immolation/combustion by inserting into a body.\n* '''Mending Key''': Opens a magical cabinet in Keyhouse into which a broken object can be placed (the cabinet can resize itself to the size of the object). Once the object is locked inside the cabinet, it is repaired. While it can heal severely wounded people, it cannot apparently resurrect the dead.\n* '''Moon Key''': Allows the user to reach and open the Moon like a door, which allows the user to pass on to the afterlife peacefully. Inhabitants who cross the door see the living world like a stage they can observe and afterlife like the backstage of a theater.\n* '''Music Box Key''': Inserted into a magical music box, it will cause the box to play a song that compels whomever is listening to obey its lyrics. Whoever turns the key can supply the commands. Commands are carried out so long as the music is playing and the listener can hear it.\n* ''' Omega Key''': Opens the lock on the demonic door. The first key created.\n* '''Owl Key''': Gives the user control of a mechanical owl.\n* '''Philosophoscope Key''': Gives access to a device that allows viewing of various people and places.\n* '''Reali Key''': Allows passage to alternate dimensions.\n* '''Shadow Key''': Allows its wearer to control shadow creatures, and even the shadows of other people. Shadows are capable of interacting with the material world (often violently) but can be rendered immaterial by bright light. Embedded in a crown, the key is a tremendous source of power for the wearer. \n* '''Skin Key''': A key with a gazing mirror on its handle, it can change the race of whoever is using it.\n* '''Small World Key''': Unlocks a dollhouse replica of Keyhouse, allowing the user to see anything in Keyhouse in realtime. Any interaction with the unlocked dollhouse also occurs within the actual house, such as a house spider entering the dollhouse magically emerging as a giant spider within the real house.\n* '''Splody Key''': Causes explosions in any building it is used within.\n* '''Squirrel/Undertree Key''': Controls squirrels.\n* '''Timeshift Key''': Operates a grandfather clock that allows a user to observe (but not interact with) past events. The clock is limited to a specific time period: the earliest date one can visit is January 13, 1775, and the latest is December 31, 1999.\n* '''Teddy Bear Key''': Animates and controls stuffed teddy bears.\n* '''Thorn Key''': Controls plants, including for offensive purposes.\n* '''Unnamed Riffel Key''': A key created by Hans Riffel, the last person to use whispering iron before Tyler. The key is to the front door of Keyhouse Manor and implements the Riffel Rule, where no one who enters the front door of the house as an adult can directly see the power of the keys. People who age into adulthood will also begin to lose their conscious memories of the keys and their magic.\n\n==Story arcs==\n\n===''Welcome to Lovecraft''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || February 20, 2008 || After the murder of their father, Tyler, Kinsey, and Bode Locke relocate with their mother to the family estate of Keyhouse, located in Lovecraft, Massachusetts. Sam Lesser, one of the teens who murdered Mr. Locke, is in a juvenile detention center and, by gazing in water, communicates with a supernatural force that promises to free him. Bode Locke, the youngest of the family, uncovers The Ghost Door, which separates his spirit from his body.\n|-\n| '''#2''' || March 26, 2008|| Bode continues to experiment with The Ghost Door and, in his incorporeal form, spies on his brother, sister, and mother. During his journeys, Bode discovers a well that houses a creature who appears as a girl, the supernatural force previously communicating with Sam Lesser.\n|-\n| '''#3''' || April 30, 2008 || Sam Lesser uses the tools the girl gave him to escape from the detention center.\n|-\n| '''#4''' || May 28, 2008 || Sam Lesser travels across America, making his way towards Keyhouse. His cross-country journey is mirrored by a series of flashbacks into his memories.\n|-\n| '''#5''' || June 25, 2008 || The Locke family is taken hostage by Sam Lesser who is seeking the Anywhere Key for his Master, the girl in the well.\n|-\n| '''#6''' || July 30, 2008 || Bode uncovers the Anywhere Key and trades it with the girl in the well for a promise that she'll stop Sam Lesser. Freed from her prison, she keeps her promise by throwing Sam through the Ghost Door with no chance to return.\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Head Games''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || January 28, 2009 || Intermission<ref name=\"sorta\" />|| Professor Joe Ridgeway recognizes Zack Wells as Lucas Caravaggio, a teenager who disappeared over twenty years before, along with several other students, and who has long been presumed dead. Joe soon sets out to dig up the truth on Wells, but Zack proves ruthless in his desire for secrecy.\n|-\n| '''#2''' || February 25, 2009 || Chapter One || A shocking death throws Kinsey and Tyler Locke into choppy emotional waters. They turn to Zack Wells for support, not knowing him to be the murderer. Meanwhile, six-year-old Bode Locke tries to puzzle out the secret of the head key, and Uncle Duncan is jarred into the past by a disturbingly familiar face.\n|-\n| '''#3''' || March 4, 2009 || Chapter Two || Kinsey, Tyler, and Bode discover the head key allows them to open up people's minds and play with their memories.\n|-\n| '''#4''' || April 8, 2009 || Chapter Three || Duncan Locke finds himself faced with a dizzying, impossible revelation; Tyler makes the ill-considered decision to share with others the unlikely powers of the head key; and Kinsey opts to remove troubling emotions from her mind.\n|-\n| '''#5''' || May 20, 2009 || Chapter Four || Dodge uses the head key on Duncan Locke, sparing his life but inadvertently leading to the injury of Locke's live-in-boyfriend.\n|-\n| '''#6''' || July 1, 2009 || Army of One<ref name=\"sorta\" />|| We learn how Dodge maintains control of Ellie even without the use of a head key in a flashback sequence.\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Crown of Shadows''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || November 11, 2009 || The Haunting of Keyhouse<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke &amp; Key: Crown of Shadows #1 \u2013 (comic book issue) \u2013 Comic Vine| url = http://www.comicvine.com/locke-key-crown-of-shadows-/37-182789/| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref>|| Sam Lesser may be dead and gone, but Dodge still has uses for him, and in the first chill days of October, will make contact with him again. The dead know things the living may not, and Sam's restless spirit has had time to discover the thing Dodge wants to know most of all... where to find the key to the black door.\n|-\n| '''#2''' || December 16, 2009 || In the Cave || Far below Keyhouse lies the Drowning Cave, a place where shadows obscure ancient secrets, and the stones are stained with ancient blood. Kinsey Locke descends into the cavern, looking for answers to her family's troubled past, only to discover that it's easier to get in than it is to get out...\n|-\n| '''#3''' || February 17, 2010 || Last Light<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke &amp; Key: Crown of Shadows #3 \u2013 Chapter Three: Last Light (comic book issue) \u2013 Comic Vine| url = http://www.comicvine.com/locke-key-crown-of-shadows-chapter-three-last-light/37-199562/| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref>|| Dodge takes possession of the crown of shadows, and darkness falls upon Keyhouse... with a vengeance.\n|-\n| '''#4''' || March 17, 2010 || Shadow Play<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke &amp; Key: Crown of Shadows #4 \u2013 Shadow Play (comic book issue) \u2013 Comic Vine| url = http://www.comicvine.com/locke-key-crown-of-shadows-shadow-play/37-205859/| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref>|| Kinsey and Bode find themselves in a desperate, seemingly unwinnable battle against a rising army of living shadows, while Tyler faces down Dodge in a terrifying duel of wits and wills.\n|-\n|-\n| '''#5''' || April 28, 2010 || Light of Day<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke &amp; Key: Crown of Shadows #5 \u2013 Chapter Five: Light of Day (comic book issue) \u2013 Comic Vine| url = http://www.comicvine.com/locke-key-crown-of-shadows-chapter-five-light-of-day/37-210310/| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref>|| The owners of the Giant Key and the Shadow Key go head to head.\n|-\n|-\n| '''#6''' || July 14, 2010 || Beyond Repair<ref>{{cite web| title = Halfway : Joe Hill Fiction| date = 2010-06-14| url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=1566| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref> || In a terrible night of grief and rage, Nina Locke discovers a new key, one which opens a cabinet capable of mending smashed objects; but some things, she will learn, are beyond repair...\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Keys to the Kingdom''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || August 11, 2010 || Sparrow<ref>{{cite web| title = The Keys to the Kingdom: Joe Hill Fiction| date = 2010-08-10| url = http://joehillfiction.com/?p=1598| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref> || As the new arc begins, Bode Locke discovers a key that unlocks the world of tooth, fang, claw, and feather, in a story that leaves hundreds dead! Hundreds of birds, that is.\n|-\n| '''#2''' || October 20, 2010<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key Keys To The Kingdom #2 (of 6)| date = 2010-08-03| url = http://www.boompanda.com/show_items.php?item=AUG100345| accessdate = 2010-09-13| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708083228/http://www.boompanda.com/show_items.php?item=AUG100345| archive-date = 2011-07-08| url-status = dead}}</ref>|| White<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke &amp; Key: Keys To The Kingdom #2 cover| date = 2010-08-03| url = http://www2.gr.cl/?p=1612| accessdate = 2010-09-13}}</ref>|| On a bitter winter day, Kinsey Locke encounters a madwoman who just might be able to unlock the darkest secrets of Keyhouse. But forcing the truth out of her won't be easy, and besides... Dodge has no intention of ever giving Erin Voss a chance to tell what she knows.\n|-\n| '''#3''' || November 24, 2010 || February || Dodge and the Locke children do battle via their keys over 29 days. The cover image shows a February 2012 calendar page (the final 2 in 2012 is obscured by a bloody hand print, but only 2012 fits, being a leap year February beginning on a Wednesday).\n|-\n| '''#4''' || January 26, 2011<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key Keys To The Kingdom #4 (of 6)| url = http://www.comixology.com/sku/NOV100371/Locke-Key-Keys-To-the-Kingdom-4-of-6-| accessdate = 2011-01-05}}</ref>|| Casualties || When Squadron Strange accept a mission from a ghost, they find themselves on their most perilous raid ever... straight into the heart of a haunted mansion. Sgt. Rufus Whedon and Corporal Bode Locke have a terrifying lesson to learn: if you're dealing with a dead man, you better think fast and fight hard, if you don't want to wind up one yourself.\n|-\n| '''#5''' || March 2, 2011<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key Keys To The Kingdom #5 (of 6)| url = http://www.comixology.com/sku/DEC100402/Locke-Key-Keys-To-the-Kingdom-5-of-6-| accessdate = 2011-02-25}}</ref>|| Detectives, Part 1 ||Tyler Locke begins, finally, to consider what he knows about the terrifying but mysterious enemy that has harrowed the Locke family for months\u2014only to find that all the evidence points to a single suspect: Zack Wells.\n|-\n| '''#6''' || April 27, 2011 || Detectives, Part 2|| 'Keys to the Kingdom' comes to a close as Dodge and Tyler Locke confront one another at last. Tyler came armed with the truth; Dodge prefers sharper instruments, and shows his willingness to use them.\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Clockworks''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || July 20, 2011<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #1 (of 6) | date = 2010-08-10| url = http://www.comixology.com/sku/APR110291/Locke-Key-Clockworks-1-of-6- }}</ref> || The Locksmith's Son || Colonel Adam Crais's minutemen are literally trapped between a rock and a hard place; in the first days of the Revolutionary War, they find themselves hiding beneath 120 feet of New England stone, with a full regiment of redcoats waiting for them in the daylight... and a door into hell in the cavern below.\n\nThe black door is open, and it's up to a 16-year-old smith named Ben Locke to find a way to close it. The biggest mysteries of the ''Locke & Key'' series are resolved as Clockworks opens, not with a bang, but with the thunderous crash of English cannons.\n|-\n| '''#2''' || August 31, 2011<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #2 (of 6) | date = 2010-08-10| url = http://www.comixology.com/sku/JUN110396/Locke-Key-Clockworks-2-of-6- }}</ref> || SMASH! || Terror runs wild, and the Locke family comes to grief in the smash-ingest story of the series yet!\n|-\n|-\n| '''#3''' || December 14, 2011<ref>{{cite web | title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #3 (of 6) | date = 2011-04-10 | url = http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-3-of-6___390958 | access-date = 2011-11-28 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111203023720/http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-3-of-6___390958 | archive-date = 2011-12-03 | url-status = dead }}</ref> || The Tamers of the Tempest || The Omega Key to The Black Door has been found by the one, who calls himself The Legion.\n|-\n|-\n| '''#4''' || February 1, 2012<ref>{{cite web | title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #4 (of 6) | date = 2011-10-17 | url = http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-4-of-6___394579 | access-date = 2011-12-05 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111227035435/http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-4-of-6___394579 | archive-date = 2011-12-27 | url-status = dead }}</ref> || The Whispering Iron || The tamers of The Tempest\u2014Rendell Locke, Dodge Caravaggio, and their friends\u2014descend into the Drowning Cave to open the Black Door, hoping to get their hands on some of the fabled whispering iron, the material from which all of the keys are forged. And everything goes according to plan! Not.\n|-\n|-\n| '''#5''' || March 14, 2012<ref>{{cite web| title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #5 (of 6) | date = 2011-11-28| url = http://dewaynes-world.popshop.comixology.com/item/NOV110301/Locke-Key-Clockworks-5-of-6- }}</ref> || Grown-Ups || Lucas \"Dodge\" Caravaggio returns from the Drowning Cave, infected by a parasite of the soul; the good and loving friend has been left behind, and replaced by something free of all human feeling. Searching for a way to control him, the Keepers of the Keys make a dreadful choice... and set off a chain of events that will end in an unimaginable slaughter.\n|-\n|-\n| '''#6''' || May 16, 2012<ref>{{cite web | title = Locke & Key: Clockworks #6 (of 6) | date = 2011-11-28 | url = http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-6-of-6___399567 | access-date = 2012-04-07 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120125090600/http://www.tfaw.com/Comics/Profile/Locke-and-Key-Clockworks-6-of-6___399567 | archive-date = 2012-01-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref> || Curtain || As a storm thunders up the coast to Lovecraft, Massachusetts, the Keepers of the Keys face Dodge a final time, under three hundred feet of stone, in the darkness before the Black Door. Here, water will mix with blood and The Drowning Cave will become a colossal grave, in the final issue of the CLOCKWORKS storyline.\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Alpha & Omega''===\nThe final arc is titled ''Locke & Key: Alpha & Omega'', and collects ''Omega'' #1\u20135, and ''Alpha'' #1\u20132.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=joe_hill|author=Joe Hill|number=342378985679884288|date=5 June 2013|title=Yes, the final hardcover is titled LOCKE &amp; KEY: ALPHA &amp; OMEGA. All 7 issues (Omega 1 - 5, Alpha 1 &amp;2) will be included.}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 80px;\"|'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| ''' ''Omega'' #1''' || November 14, 2012 || Our Regrets || The beginning of the end starts here. Dodge has the Omega key, and nothing can stop him from using it...\n|-\n| ''' ''Omega'' #2''' || December 19, 2012 || The Soldier || A ghost haunts the long halls of Keyhouse\u2014the spirit of Bode Locke, cast out of his body by the Demon named Dodge\u2014and only one person can hear his voice: Bode's old playmate, Rufus Whedon.<ref>[http://www.legionofcomics.co.uk/acatalog/LOCKE___KEY_OMEGA__2.html Legionofcomics.co.uk]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''' ''Omega'' #3''' || February 20, 2013 || Last Dance || As Kinsey Locke and the other students head to a dance at Lovecraft Academy, the demonic Dodge gathers shadowy forces of his own and enacts his evil endgame. The \u201cLast Dance\u201d begins here.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.inter-comics.com/shop/locke-key-omega-3-of-7 |title=Inter-comics.com |access-date=2012-12-11 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127025453/https://www.inter-comics.com/shop/locke-key-omega-3-of-7 |archive-date=2013-01-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''' ''Omega'' #4''' || April 3, 2013 || Human Sacrifices|| The bottomless pit of the Drowning Cave threatens to become a mass grave, as Dodge springs a fatal trap on the senior class of Lovecraft Academy. Hope is as fragile as a candle-flame wavering in the night. . . and as easy to extinguish.\n|-\n| ''' ''Omega'' #5''' || June 5, 2013 || The Fall || In the Drowning Cave, the black door is open at last, and for the kids trapped down there, the choice is simple: resist and die, or pass through the door and be lost forever. In the hole beneath Keyhouse the stones run with blood, the living shadows run riot, and time runs out... as ''Locke & Key'' enters its final chapters.\n|-\n| ''' ''Alpha'' #1'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Phegley|first=Kiel|title=C2E2: New Books Make Waves at Diamond Summit|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=45138|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=27 April 2013}}</ref> || September 11, 2013<ref>{{cite tweet|user=IDWPublishing|author=IDW Publishing|number=372761461451276289|date=28 August 2013|title=Locke &amp; Key: Alpha #1 will be out on 9/11/13. Sorry for the delay, but this is one that couldn't be rushed. Perfection takes time.}}</ref> || Alpha ||In the penultimate issue of ''Locke & Key'', the damned and the saved alike will make their final stand in the Drowning Cave, in a clash of blood and fire. The shadows have never been darker and the end has never been closer. Turn the key and open the last door; it's time to say goodbye.<ref>[http://www.previewsworld.com/Home/1/1/71/916?stockItemID=JUN130329 Previewsworld.com]</ref>\n|-\n| ''' ''Alpha'' #2''' ||December 18, 2013<ref name=\"Ryallsfiles\">[http://ryallsfiles.tumblr.com/post/66916898702/advance-copies-of-the-final-issue-of-locke-key Ryallsfiles]</ref>|| The Last Door ||\"The End.\" A door claps softly shut. A key scrapes in a last rusted lock. It ends here: the story of the Locke children and their desperate, tragic battle with the monster set on destroying them... the past.<ref name=\"previewsworld.com\">[http://www.previewsworld.com/Home/1/1/71/916?stockItemID=AUG130400 Previewsworld.com]</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===''World War Key''===\nAt the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], Joe Hill confirmed that a new ''Locke & Key'' series called ''World War Key'' was in the works.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/horror/2019/08/18/locke-and-key-new-comics-netflix-series-joe-hill-world-war-key/|title=Locke & Key Creators Confirm More Comics Are on the Way|last=Lovett|first=Jamie|date=August 18, 2019|website=comicbook.com}}</ref> This storyline as Hill puts it is ''\"about the idea that the past is never gone... and I think a lot of ghost stories are about ways the past keep bleeding through to the present. We'll visit the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]], [[American Civil War|Civil War]], and [[World War II]] to show how those past events have had lingering effects on our heroes today.\"''<ref name=\":1\" /> As of 2019, the series is expected to run thirty-seven issues across six books (not including \"The Golden Age\").<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hill |first1=Joe |last2=Rodriguez |first2=Gabriel |title=Locke & Key: Small World |publisher=IDW |location=Interview: \"A Conversation about Locke & Key\"}}</ref> ''World War Key'' is designed to be both a prequel and a sequel to the original run of ''Locke & Key''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Skye |first1=Louis |title=10 Years of Locke and Key: The Creators on the Journey So Far |url=https://womenwriteaboutcomics.com/2018/04/10-years-of-locke-and-key-the-creators-on-the-journey-so-far/ |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''The Golden Age''====\nA series of short stories set in the past.<ref>{{cite news|last=Truitt|first=Brian|title=Joe Hill hopes to \"stick the landing\" for \"Locke & Key\"|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2012/11/13/joe-hill-locke-key-omega-comic-book-series/1702663/|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 April 2013|date=November 13, 2012}}</ref> In his newsletter, Joe Hill referred to the book as \"''World War Key 0: The Golden Age''\".<ref name=\"EH037\">{{cite web |last1=Hill |first1=Joe |title=Escape Hatch 037: Ride On |url=https://mailchi.mp/joehillfiction/escape-hatch-037-ride-on?e=a00c7b5aaf |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Locke & Key: In Pale Battalions Go'' will be a two-issue story that leads into ''World War Key'', set at the beginning of the 20th century and will feature characters from \"Small World\" and \"Open the Moon\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Locke & Key's Next Comic Will Be a 'Gateway to a Larger Story' |url=https://www.cbr.com/locke-key-battalions-one-shot-announced/ |website=cbr.co |publisher=cbr.com}}</ref> It will also lead into the ''Locke & Key/Sandman Universe'' crossover comic.<ref name=\"EH037\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 190px;\"|'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''''Guide to the Known Keys''''' || November 23, 2011 || This special standalone issue features an expanded \"Guide to the Known Keys\", an all-new \"Guide to Failed Keys\", and a story of summer night magic titled \"Open the Moon\", set in Keyhouse's unlikely past.\n|-\n| '''''Grindhouse''''' || August 29, 2012 || Set in the glare of a Depression-era summer, in which three Canuck gangsters carry out a heist and hide out at the Keyhouse. ''Locke & Key: Grindhouse'' includes an expanded \"Guide to Keyhouse\" describing the mansion.\n|-\n| '''''Small World''''' || December 21, 2016 || An impossible birthday gift for two little girls unexpectedly throws open a door to a monster on eight legs. Joe Hill has said that the title is a shout out to the horror novel of the same name by his mother [[Tabitha King]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnston|first=Rich|title=A Locke & Key Christmas Miracle From Joe Hill And Gabriel Rodriguez|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2016/06/15/a-locke-key-christmas-miracle-from-joe-hill-and-gabriel-rodriguez/|publisher=Bleeding Cool Comic Book, Movie, TV News|accessdate=June 15, 2016|date=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''Nailed It''''' || July 19, 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsarama.com/45936-idw-rolls-out-sdcc-plans-as-it-celebrates-its-20th-comic-con.html|title=IDW Rolls Out SDCC Plans as It Celebrates Its 20th Comic-Con|last=Staff|first=Newsarama|date=July 9, 2019|website=Newsarama|access-date=July 30, 2019}}</ref> || A 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] Exclusive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idwpublishing.com/idw-announces-signing-schedule-panels-and-exclusives-for-san-diego-comic-con-international-2019/|title=IDW Announces Signing Schedule, Panels, and Exclusives for San Diego Comic-Con International 2019|last=Publishing|first=IDW|date=July 9, 2019|website=IDW Publishing|access-date=July 30, 2019}}</ref> \"Some doors, once closed, can never be opened again. While others shouldn\u2019t be reopened ever again\u2026\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2019/07/29/locke-key-namejoe-hill-martin-simmonds/|title=Locke & Key Changes Name, New Series by Joe Hill and Martin Simmonds to be Previewed|last=Johnston|first=Rich|date=July 29, 2019|website=Bleeding Cool|access-date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''Dog Days''''' || November 6, 2019 || A 48-page special containing \"Dog Days\" and recollecting \"Nailed It\" in one issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icv2.com/articles/news/view/43742/joe-hill-gabriel-rodriguez-return-locke-key|title=JOE HILL AND GABRIEL RODRIGUEZ RETURN TO 'LOCKE & KEY'|last=Alverson|first=Brigid|date=August 1, 2019|website=ICv2|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> Two boys of the Locke family use the Animal Key to turn their pet dog into a human boy.\n|-\n|'''''In Pale Battalions Go'' #1'''<ref name=\"Cover 1 reveal\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/GR_comics/status/1249121481369534467|title=Gabriel Rodriguez Twitter|last=Rodriguez|first=Gabriel|date=April 11, 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> || 2020 || TBA\n|-\n|'''''In Pale Battalions Go'' #2''' || 2020 || TBA\n|}\n\n====Revolution====\nThe first arc of ''World War Key''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n|'''#1''' ||2020<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/joehill/comments/cgxket/more_locke_and_key_coming_in_2020_image_from_the/|title=More Locke and Key coming in 2020 (image from the SDCC \u201cNailed It\u201d comic)|last=Kwyjibo331|first=u/|date=July 23, 2019|website=Reddit|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref> || TBD || TBD\n|}\n\n===\"Hell & Gone\"===\nOn February 21st 2020 IDW announced via their twitter<ref>{{cite web |title=LOCKE & KEY: HELL & GONE - A SANDMAN UNIVERSE Crossover Event |url=https://twitter.com/IDWPublishing/status/1231017077890277376?ref_src=twsrc^tfw |website=twitter.com |publisher=IDW Publishing}}</ref> that ''Locke & Key'' would be crossing over with [[DC Comics]]'s ''[[The Sandman Universe|Sandman Universe]]'', the story will center around DC's Key to Hell from ''The Sandman'' story arc \"Season of Mists\".\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!'''Issue''' !! '''Release''' !! '''Chapter Title''' !! '''Summary'''\n|-\n| '''#1''' || October 2020 || TBD|| TBD\n|}\n\n==Collected editions==\n\n===Standard editions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Volume''' !! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 130px;\"|'''Release''' !! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 140px;\"|'''Title''' !! '''Summary''' !!scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 190px;\"| '''ISBN'''\n|-\n| '''1''' || October 8, 2008 || ''Locke & Key<br />Welcome to Lovecraft'' || Collects ''Welcome to Lovecraft'' #1\u20136 || {{ISBNT|9781600102370}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781600103841}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''2''' || September 30, 2009 || ''Locke & Key<br />Head Games ''|| Collects ''Head Games'' #1\u20136 || {{ISBNT|9781600104831}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781600107610}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''3''' || July 29, 2010 || ''Locke & Key<br />Crown of Shadows'' || Collects ''Crown of Shadows'' #1\u20136 || {{ISBNT|9781600106958}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781600109539}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''4''' || July 19, 2011 || ''Locke & Key<br />Keys to the Kingdom ''|| Collects ''Keys to the Kingdom'' #1\u20136 || {{ISBNT|9781600108860}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781613772072}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''5''' || July 24, 2012 || ''Locke & Key<br />Clockworks'' || Collects ''Clockworks'' #1\u20136 || {{ISBNT|9781613772270}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781613776995}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''6''' || February 4, 2014 || ''Locke & Key<br />Alpha & Omega'' || Collects ''Omega'' #1\u20135 and ''Alpha'' #1\u20132 || {{ISBNT|9781613778531}} (Hardcover)<br />{{ISBNT|9781631401442}} (Paperback)\n|-\n| '''\u2014''' || January 4, 2017 || ''Locke & Key<br />Small World''<ref>{{cite news|title=Locke & Key: Small World (Preview)|url=http://www.cbr.com/locke-key-small-world/|publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]]|accessdate=September 12, 2017|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> || Collects ''The Golden Age'' stand-alone issue ''Small World''. || {{ISBNT|9781631408465}} (Hardcover)\n|-\n| '''\u2014''' || August 15, 2017 || ''Locke & Key<br />Heaven and Earth''<ref>{{cite news|last=Ching|first=Albert|title=Rare Locke & Key One-Shots Collected In New Hardcover|url=http://www.cbr.com/locke-and-key-heaven-and-earth-hardcover/|publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]]|accessdate=April 17, 2017|date=April 12, 2017}}</ref> || Collects ''The Golden Age'' stand-alone short stories \"Open the Moon\", ''Grindhouse'', and \"In the Can\", (a rare ''Locke and Key'' short that was published in ''IDW: 10 Year Anniversary Comic Book'' in 2009) || {{ISBNT|9781684051816}} (Hardcover)\n|}\n\nOn November 11, 2014, the first six volumes were collected as a slipcase set of paperbacks.\n\n===Master editions===\n''Locke & Key'' was also collected in three hardcover books with all-new cover art and design by Gabriel Rodriguez.\n* '''''Locke & Key Master Edition Volume 1''''' (May 19, 2015). Collects the first two arcs, ''Welcome to Lovecraft'' and ''Head Games''.\n* '''''Locke & Key Master Edition Volume 2''''' (March 22, 2016). Collects the third and fourth arcs, ''Crown of Shadows'' and ''Keys to the Kingdom''.\n* '''''Locke & Key Master Edition Volume 3''''' (October 18, 2016). Collects the fifth and sixth arcs, ''Clockworks'' and ''Alpha & Omega''.\n\n===Signed limited editions===\nOn November 11, 2007, [[Subterranean Press]] announced a pre-order for a hand-numbered, signed, limited edition of the six-issue run of ''Welcome To Lovecraft''. This edition consisted of 250 numbered copies and 26 lettered copies, both of which sold out within 24 hours of being announced.<ref>{{cite web| title = Teaser \u2014 Locke & Key by Joe Hill| publisher = [[Subterranean Press]]| date = 2007-11-11| url = http://subterraneanpress.com/index.php/2007/11/11/teaser-locke-key-by-joe-hill/| accessdate = 2008-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Limited and Lettered LOCKE & KEY by Joe Hill Sold Out| publisher = [[Subterranean Press]]| date = 2007-11-24| url = http://subterraneanpress.com/index.php/2007/11/24/limited-and-lettered-locke-key-by-joe-hill-sold-out/| accessdate = 2008-12-09| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080820155436/http://subterraneanpress.com/index.php/2007/11/24/limited-and-lettered-locke-key-by-joe-hill-sold-out| archivedate = 2008-08-20}}</ref> This edition was a hardcover release in a specially designed and illustrated slipcase, and featured exclusive dust jacket art by [[Vincent Chong]] and reprinted all 250 pages of [[Joe Hill (writer)|Joe Hill]]'s script in addition to the actual comic work.<ref>{{cite web| title = Joe Hill \u2014 LOCKE & KEY Update| publisher = [[Subterranean Press]]| date = 2008-06-07| url = http://subterraneanpress.com/index.php/2008/06/07/joe-hill-locke-key-update/| accessdate = 2008-12-09}}</ref>\n\nThis was followed by the publication of ''Head Games'', which was also limited to 250 hand-numbered and signed copies as well as 26 lettered copies.<ref>{{cite web| title = Joe Hill \u2014 discovered an amazing singer tamia d. holder who will soon be working tour with mindless behavior and more she will be the n.b.t out there for single song writer already has 2 songs of her own.| publisher = [[Subterranean Press]]| date = 2009-04-27| url = http://subterraneanpress.com/index.php/2009/04/27/joe-hill-head-games-is-coming-to-subterranean/| accessdate = 2011-02-12}}</ref>\nThe third volume, ''Crown of Shadows'', is available for preorder, and like the previous editions is signed and numbered with the same limitations and also comes with an illustrated slipcase.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://subterraneanpress.com/store/product_detail/locke_key_crown_of_shadows |title=Subterraneanpress.com |access-date=2013-01-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117074554/http://subterraneanpress.com/store/product_detail/locke_key_crown_of_shadows |archive-date=2013-01-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nCloth-bound trade editions limited to 1000 copies (unsigned, unnumbered, and without the slipcase) were also released. Trade editions for the first two volumes are sold out.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nAt the 2009 [[Eisner Awards]], ''Locke & Key'' was nominated for Best Limited Series and Joe Hill was nominated for Best Writer.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nIt won the 2009 [[British Fantasy Award]] for Best Comic or Graphic Novel.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nIt won the 2011 Eisner Award for Best Writer (Joe Hill), and was nominated for Best Single Issue, Best Continuing Series, and Best Penciller.\n\nIt won the 2012 [[British Fantasy Award]] for Best Comic or Graphic Novel.<ref>{{cite web|title=British Fantasy Awards 2012|url=http://www.britishfantasysociety.co.uk/news/british-fantasy-awards-2012/|work=yes|publisher=British Fantasy Society|accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\nA film trilogy was officially announced at the 2014 Comic Con. [[Alex Kurtzman]], [[Roberto Orci]], [[Bobby Cohen]] and Ted Adams would produce the film with [[Universal Pictures]] and Kurtzman and Orci's production company [[K/O Paper Products]].<ref>Kit, Borys (June 19, 2013). [http://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/universal-picks-up-locke-key-571840 \"Universal Picks Up 'Locke & Key' Comic\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Joe Hill confirmed that the films are no longer happening. However, he stated that TV series is still possible.<ref>DiVincenzo, Alex (October 5, 2015). [http://brokehorrorfan.com/post/130564700528/i-had-the-pleasure-of-meeting-author-joe-hill-at-a \"Locke & Key Film Adaptation Dead, TV Series Still Possible\"]. ''Broke Horror Fan''.</ref> In May 2016, Joe Hill announced he would write a TV pilot, serve as executive producer and pitch the show to various networks and streaming companies.<ref>Goncalves, Sarah (May 2016). [http://screenrant.com/locke-key-tv-show-joe-hill/ \"Locke & Key TV Series With Joe Hill Moving Forward\"].</ref>\n\n===Television===\n\n====Fox pilot (2010\u20132011)====\n{{see also|Locke & Key (TV pilot)}}\n\n[[Dimension Films]] acquired the film and television rights for ''Welcome to Lovecraft'' from [[IDW Publishing]] with the intent of developing the property as a feature with [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] producing.<ref>[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18977 Dimension Loses Rights to Joe Hill's Awesome 'Locke & Key' Comic!]</ref> In February 2010, it was announced that Dimension had lost the adaptation rights to Dreamworks<ref>[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35715/dreamworks-keeping-newly-acquired-property-under-locke-key DreamWorks Keeping Newly Acquired Property Under Locke & Key]</ref> with [[Alex Kurtzman]] and [[Roberto Orci]] signed on to develop and produce the project.<ref>[http://www.latinoreview.com/news/exclusive-kurtzman-orci-to-produce-locke-key-9138 Exclusive: Kurtzman & Orci To Produce Locke & Key]</ref> In August 2010 [[Steven Spielberg]] also joined as a producer, and the production became a TV series rather than a movie adaptation, with [[Josh Friedman]] writing episodes for the show and acting as show-runner.<ref>[http://leagueofcomicgeeks.com/news/335/locke-and-key-adaptation-becomes-tv-series Locke & Key Adaptation Becomes TV Series]</ref>\n\nThe TV series adaptation then landed at [[20th Century Fox Television]]. The network greenlit a [[pilot episode|pilot]], produced by [[Dreamworks TV]] and [[K/O Paper Products]] through the latter's deal with 20th Century Fox TV.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Schneider|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118026326.html?categoryid=14&cs=1|title=Fox greenlights 'Locke and Key'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2010-10-25|accessdate=2010-10-26}}</ref>\n\n[[Miranda Otto]] played Nina Locke, [[Sarah Bolger]] was Kinsey Locke<ref>{{Cite news|first=Scott|last=Tady|title=Pilot for new TV show show in Pittsburgh|date=2010-11-26 |newspaper=[[Beaver County Times]]|url=http://www.timesonline.com/bct_news/news_details/article/1373/2010/november/26/pilot-for-new-tv-show-show-in-pittsburgh.html| accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first=Cathy|last=Hayes|title=Irish Sarah Bolger cast in Fox\u2019s 'Locke & Key'|date=2010-12-20|publisher=IrishCentral|url= http://www.irishcentral.com/ent/Irish-Sarah-Bolger-cast-in-Foxs-Locke--Key-112181554.html|accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref> and [[Nick Stahl]] co-starred as Duncan Locke.<ref>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Wigler|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/01/13/nick-stahl-joins-locke-key-fox-targets-fall-premiere/|title=Nick Stahl Joins 'Locke & Key,' FOX Targets Fall Premiere|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=2011-01-13|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> Skylar Gaertner played 6-year old Bode, and Harrison Thomas played a teenager possessed by an evil spirit.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/01/bones-spinoff-the-finder-finds-lead/ |title='Bones' Spinoff 'The Finder' Finds Lead |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 28, 2011 |accessdate=February 4, 2011 }}</ref> Actor and singer [[Jesse McCartney]] appeared as Ty Locke, the series' male lead<ref>{{cite web |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/02/jesse-mccartney-to-star-in-foxs-lock-key/ |title=Jesse McCartney To Star In 'Locke & Key' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 3, 2011 |accessdate=February 4, 2011 }}</ref> and [[Ksenia Solo]] was cast as Dodge.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kevin |last=Melrose |url=http://spinoff.comicbookresources.com/2011/02/21/foxs-locke-key-finds-its-dodge/ |title=Fox\u2019s Locke & Key Finds Its Dodge |publisher= |date=February 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Romanek]] directed the pilot episode,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jeff |last=Leins |url=http://www.newsinfilm.com/2010/11/23/mark-romanek-to-direct-locke-key-tv-pilot/ |title=Mark Romanek to Direct 'Locke & Key' TV Pilot |work=News in Film |date=November 23, 2010 |access-date=November 24, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603170819/http://www.newsinfilm.com/2010/11/23/mark-romanek-to-direct-locke-key-tv-pilot/ |archive-date=June 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which was filmed at the mansion in [[Hartwood Acres]] and in [[Ellwood City, Pennsylvania]], in February 2011. The pilot was also shot throughout [[Pittsburgh]] that same month.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Owen |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11042/1124560-67.stm/ |title=Tuned In: Fox pilot 'Locke & Key' filming in Pittsburgh |publisher= post-gazette.com |date=February 11, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2011 }}</ref> In May 2011, Fox announced that the project would not be picked up to the series.<ref>{{cite news|last=Owen|first=Rob|title=Fox reportedly passes on 'Locke & Key'|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11131/1145721-100.stm|accessdate=11 May 2011|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=11 May 2011}}</ref> The studio attempted to sell the project to other networks but eventually ceased efforts due to rising costs. The pilot was screened at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]], where it was well received.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/06/fox-pilot-locke-key-to-screen-at-comic-con/|title=Fox Pilot 'Locke & Key' To Screen At Comic-Con |website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 22, 2011|accessdate=June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Hulu pilot (2017\u20132018)====\n\nOn April 20, 2017, [[Hulu]] ordered a pilot based on the comic with [[Carlton Cuse]], [[Scott Derrickson]], and Lindsey Springer as producers.<ref>{{cite web|first=Daniel|last=Holloway|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/hulu-carlton-cuse-1202391596/|title=Hulu Orders Carlton Cuse Pilot \u2018Locke and Key\u2019|publisher=Variety|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> In July 2017, Derrickson was replaced by [[Andy Muschietti]] as the pilot's director.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/locke-key-andy-muschietti-replace-scott-derrickson-director-hulu-pilot-1202129058/|title=\u2018Locke and Key\u2019: Andy Muschietti To Direct Hulu Pilot Based On Graphic Novel|date=14 July 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, [[Frances O'Connor]] was cast as Nina in the show.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=http://deadline.com/2017/08/locke-key-frances-oconnor-cast-star-hulu-pilot-carlton-cuse-joe-hill-1202150760/|title=\u2018Locke and Key\u2019: Frances O\u2019Connor To Star In Hulu Pilot From Carlton Cuse & Joe Hill|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=14 July 2017}}</ref> In a March 2018 interview, Samantha Mathis revealed that Hulu had passed on the show, and it was now being shopped around to other networks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://culturedvultures.com/sxsw-2018-logan-miller-samantha-mathis-talk-you-can-choose-your-family/|title=SXSW 2018: Logan Miller & Samantha Mathis Talk You Can Choose Your Family|date=2018-03-23|work=Cultured Vultures|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====Netflix series (2020)====\n{{see also|Locke & Key (TV series)}}\n\nOn May 30, 2018, after Hulu had passed on ''Locke & Key'', it was announced that [[Netflix]] was nearing a series order for a re-developed version of the show with Cuse and Hill involved once again, and Muschietti as executive producer. The show found a new director for the pilot and an entirely new cast with the exception of [[Jackson Robert Scott]] as Bode Locke, who was cast in the Hulu pilot as well.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/locke-key-drama-from-carlton-cuse-joe-hill-close-to-series-order-at-netflix-1202398905/|title=\u2018Locke & Key\u2019 Drama From Carlton Cuse & Joe Hill Nears Series Order At Netflix|website=Deadline|date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeason one of the show, with 10 episodes, debuted on Netflix on February 7th, 2020.\n\n===Audio drama===\nAll six books of ''Locke & Key'' were adapted as a 13-hour [[audio drama]] released on 5 October 2015. Produced by the [[AudioComics Company]] for [[Audible.com|Audible]] Studios and directed by William Dufris, the work features the voices of [[Tatiana Maslany]], [[Haley Joel Osment]], [[Kate Mulgrew]], with appearances by Hill, Rodr\u00edguez, and [[Stephen King]] in addition to almost 50 voice-over actors<ref>{{cite web|last=Zalben|first=Alex|title='Locke & Key' Is Coming Back \u2014 With Tatiana Maslany And An All-Star Cast|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2199716/locke-and-key-audio-book-audible/|date=7 July 2015|publisher=MTV|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref> and an original score by Peter Van Riet. The work received critical praise, and in 2016 was nominated for four Audie Awards from the Audiobook Publisher's Association of America, including \"Best Original Work\" and \"Excellence in Production.\"\n\n===Card game===\nIn 2012, Cryptozoic Entertainment released a card game based on the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=Debi|title=''Locke & Key: The Game Now Available from Cryptozoic Entertainment''|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/31176/locke-key-the-game-now-available-from-cryptozoic-entertainment/|date=22 February 2012|publisher=Dread Central|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Lost Room]] - Prior work from 2006 with a very similar main concept to ''Locke & Key'', a set of magical objects with different properties including a key that opens any door to anywhere.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{gcdb series|id=29935|title=Locke & Key: Welcome to Lovecraft}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=17073|title=''Locke & Key: Welcome to Lovecraft''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=35508|title=Locke & Key: Head Games }}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=22187|title=''Locke & Key: Head Games ''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=44506|title=Locke & Key: Crown of Shadows}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=25930|title=''Locke & Key: Crown of Shadows''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=51870|title=Locke & Key: Keys to the Kingdom}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=30137|title=''Locke & Key: Keys to the Kingdom''}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://joehillfiction.com/?cat=8 ''Locke & Key'' section] at [[Joe Hill (writer)|Joe Hill]]'s website\n* [http://gabrielrodriguez.deviantart.com Gabriel Rodriguez's online gallery] at [[DeviantArt]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100101213343/http://idwpublishing.com/catalog/series/408 ''Locke & Key'' section] at [[IDW Publishing]]'s website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081207000650/http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=122865 Interview with Joe Hill about the series] at [[Newsarama]]\n* [http://www.tfaw.com/blog/2009/10/26/writer-joe-hill-talks-to-tfaw-com-about-locke-key-from-idw/?qt=ea_L&Kwiki1 Writer Joe Hill Talks to TFAW.com About ''Locke & Key'' From IDW]\n* [http://www.dinova.cl/es/buscar?orderby=position&orderway=desc&search_query=locke+key&submit_search=Buscar Chilean version (Spanish language book)] at [http://www.dinova.cl Librer\u00eda Dinova]\n\n{{Joe Hill}}\n{{IDW Publishing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locke and Key}}\n[[Category:2009 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos comics]]\n[[Category:Comics set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Fiction about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy]]\n", "name_user": "Hellboybookeeper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld War Key", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locke_%26_Key"}
{"title_page": "Oranjehof", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n|name     = Oranjehof Dutch Connection Centre\n|image    = [[File:Welcome Wall.jpg|thumb]]\n|location = 92 Main Street, Foxton, New Zealand\n|website  = {{url|www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Bicycle handle bars with Fietsbel.jpg|thumb|Bicycle - Met Delfts Blauwe Fietsbel ]]\nThe '''Oranjehof''' '''Dutch Connection Centre''' is one of the two museums that are part of the multi-cultural, multi-purpose visitor and community hub [[Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom]] in [[Foxton, New Zealand|Foxton]], just over an hour's drive north of [[Wellington]]. \n\nThe award-winning facility<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1805/S00208/2018-serviceiq-new-zealand-museum-awards-winners-announced.htm%20Museums%20Aotearoa%20'Project%20Excellence'%20Award%5D|title=Museums Aotearoa Project Excellence award}}</ref> is also the home of the [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre Piriharakeke] museum, a library, community rooms, a gallery, a heritage room, a Council Service Centre and an [https://www.newzealand.com/us/plan/business/foxton-i-site-visitor-information-centre/ i-SITE desk].\n\nThe Oranjehof museum was created with wide support from the Dutch community in New Zealand. In addition to telling the story of the Dutch in New Zealand - it also is a centre for Dutch culture, language and [https://teara.govt.nz/en/dutch/page-3%20Dutch%20immigrants community].\n\nOranjehof is an integral part of the Te Awahou Riverside Cultural Park, which also features two Dutch-inspired cafes, and the flour-grinding windmill [http://www.foxtonwindmill.co.nz/de-molen.html De Molen].\n\nThe [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Trust Dutch Connection Museum Trust] collaborated in partnership with Horowhenua District Council, and the [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre/Te-Taitoa-Maori-o-Te-Awahou-Trust Te Taitoa M\u0101ori o Te Awahou Trust] to create the Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom facility - the home of the Oranjehof Dutch Connection Centre.\n\n== An Unknown Story == \n[[File:Gepakt en gezakt - Dutch immigrant stories.jpg|thumb|Gepakt en gezakt - Dutch immigrant stories]]\nThe Dutch \u2013 and their children and grandchildren \u2013 helped to change New Zealand and transform into a more diverse, multi-cultural nation since the 1950s and 1960s<ref>https://uhcl.recollect.co.nz/nodes/view/25708</ref>. They arrived as the first big wave of non-English speaking immigrants, in what was then still a strongly British nation.\n\nDutch migrants were issued an \u2018Alien Pass\u2019 and told to become \u2018New Britishers\u2019. The directive from both Dutch and New Zealand Governments was to merge into mainstream society. It became the norm to ignore the culture of origin, and speak English at home.<ref>http://www.netherlandsfoundation.org.nz/our-stories/read-our-stories/tasman-s-legacy/</ref>\n\n=== Invisible Immigrants ===\n[[File:Abel Tasman - Arrival in 1642.jpg|thumb|Abel Tasman - Arrival in 1642]]\nAs a result, the Dutch became the \u2018Invisible Immigrants\u2019<ref>https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/the-invisible-immigrants/</ref>, as they integrated into mainstream society<ref>http://www.caddanz.org.nz/massey/fms/Research/ntom/Home-Abroad-A-Profile-of-the-Dutch-Diaspora-in-New-Zealand.pdf?D922BDB365A154782D05E8DF9E19906E</ref>. In a way, the Dutch migrants are missing from the pages of history. Michael King, in his Penguin \u2018History of New Zealand\u2019 tells the story of all migrant groups<ref>http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/docs/2004/NZJH_38_1_07.pdf</ref> \u2013 except the Dutch. Oranjehof is the place that addresses that omission. \n\nToday, at least one in every 40 or so New Zealanders has some Dutch heritage or connections<ref>http://www.caddanz.org.nz/massey/fms/Research/ntom/Home-Abroad-A-Profile-of-the-Dutch-Diaspora-in-New-Zealand.pdf?D922BDB365A154782D05E8DF9E19906E</ref>. These hard-working arrivals influenced the tastes of a nation \u2013 in the arts, dance, religion, food. Oranjehof tells those eye-opening stories in interactive ways, which include digital displays and hands-on games. \n\nThe history of the Dutch in Aotearoa goes all the way back to Tasman's arrival in 1642, some 127 years before Captain Cook<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel_Tasman</ref>.\n\n== Oranjehof Museum ==\n[[File:Kunst - Art and design.jpg|thumb|Kunst - Art and design]]\nOranjehof is a museum that is quintessential Dutch, with a colourful sense of humour of its own, plenty of gezelligheid, and a sense of clear Dutch design. \n\nDutch artists represented, include photographer [http://suite.co.nz/answestra Ans Westra], sculptor [http://www.gibbsfarm.org.nz/vandeneijkel.php Leon van den Eijkel]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_van_den_Eijkel</ref>, and ceramicists [https://www.cordys.co.nz/auctions/Z12/catalogue Anneke Borren] and [http://www.newzealandpottery.net/t3512-melis-van-der-sluis Melis van der Sluis]. Designers include fashion icon [[Doris de Pont]] and [https://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/topic/886 Frank Carpay] who worked for Crown Lynn and also had a major impact on textile and graphic design<ref>https://www.art-newzealand.com/Issue109/carpay.htm</ref>.\n\n=== Dutch Connections ===\nThe story of the Dutch in New Zealand touches on many aspects of Kiwi life<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Carpay</ref><ref>http://www.nzfashionmuseum.org.nz/doris-de-pont</ref>. The origins of Vogel\u2019s bread, Verkerks salami, and artisan Gouda and Edam cheeses are all Dutch.  Many New Zealanders have lived in a Lockwood home, or drank coffee at [https://nzhistory.govt.nz/media/photo/interior-suzy%26%23039%3Bs-coffee-bar Suzy\u2019s Coffee Lounge] \u2013 the \u2018Queen of the Coffee Houses\u2019 in Wellington<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/108528916/wellington-cafe-legend-suzy-van-der-kwast-has-died-aged-80</ref>. \n\nA \u2018touch of Dutch\u2019 can be found just about anywhere in New Zealand \u2013 even in the country\u2019s name, due to the arrival of Abel Tasman and the first European encounter with the Maori<ref>https://nzhistory.govt.nz/people/abel-tasman</ref>. \n\n== The Exhibition and Collection ==\n[[File:Zand zeep soda.jpg|thumb|Keukenspul - Dutch kitchen]]\nOranjehof preserves Dutch heritage \u2013 history, treasures, art, language, identity, culture, Nederlandse dingen.\nAs the Dutch Connection Centre, it is the centrepoint for the Dutch community in New Zealand. \n\nOranjehof showcases:\n* Tasman's travels  \u2013 The first meeting of two worlds, M\u0101ori and P\u0101keh\u0101\n* The story of why so many Nederlanders ventured to Aotearoa\n* The Dutch influence on art and design - And on coffee culture, cheese making, agriculture and dairy\n* Nederlandse Taal \u2013 You can listen to Dutch language on Dutch radio\n* Traditional games - Plus dress up costumes for selfies \n\n== De Molen Windmill ==\n[[File:Molen lights.jpg|thumb|De Molen and Te Awahou front]]\nThe full size replica of a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[windmill]], De Molen,  was completed and opened in 2003<ref>http://www.timberdesign.org.nz/journal/case-studies/demolen-a-traditional-dutch-windmill-and-shining/</ref> and underwent some major repairs in 2018<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/102784075/landmark-foxton-windmill-de-molen-to-run-again-after-repairs</ref>.  \n\nDe Molen is the result of Netherlands-New Zealand collaboration. Running gear, millstones and sails were produced and installed by Vaags Molenwerken in Aalten, the Netherlands. The mill was built largely by volunteers, under the direction of local builder Cor Slobbe.<ref>https://www.timberdesign.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/De-Molen-The-Wooden-Design-inside.pdf</ref> The 17th century design with wooden beams is impressive to behold, especially when the mill is creaking loudly and the parts are moving, as it grinds flour on windy days.\n\nThe fully working [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/stellingmolen Stellingmolen] windmill produces stone-ground [[flour]], which can be purchased inside the mill's Dutch Deli. Visitors can climb up three floors, to witness the wooden mechanical workings of the mill in action - examples of traditional Dutch 17th Century engineering. The miller sets the blades in motion on windy days, and is available for tours to explain the history of milling, or for a more casual conversation.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre Oranjehof Museum]\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre Piriharakeke museum]\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Home Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom]\n* [http://www.foxtonwindmill.co.nz/de-molen.html De Molen - In the Cultural Park]\n* [https://www.foxton.org.nz/attr-flax.html Flax Stripper Museum - In the Cultural Park]\n\n== References  ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n|name     = Oranjehof Dutch Connection Centre\n|image    = [[File:Welcome Wall.jpg|thumb]]\n|location = 92 Main Street, Foxton, New Zealand\n|website  = {{url|www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Bicycle handle bars with Fietsbel.jpg|thumb|Bicycle - Met Delfts Blauwe Fietsbel ]]\nThe '''Oranjehof''' '''Dutch Connection Centre''' is one of the two museums that are part of the multi-cultural, multi-purpose visitor and community hub [[Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom]] in [[Foxton, New Zealand|Foxton]], just over an hour's drive north of [[Wellington]]. \n\nThe award-winning facility<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1805/S00208/2018-serviceiq-new-zealand-museum-awards-winners-announced.htm%20Museums%20Aotearoa%20'Project%20Excellence'%20Award%5D|title=Museums Aotearoa Project Excellence award}}</ref> is also the home of the [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre Piriharakeke] museum, a library, community rooms, a gallery, a heritage room, a Council Service Centre and an [https://www.newzealand.com/us/plan/business/foxton-i-site-visitor-information-centre/ i-SITE desk].\n\nThe Oranjehof museum was created with wide support from the Dutch community in New Zealand. In addition to telling the story of the Dutch in New Zealand - it also is a centre for Dutch culture, language and [https://teara.govt.nz/en/dutch/page-3%20Dutch%20immigrants community].\n\nOranjehof is an integral part of the Te Awahou Riverside Cultural Park, which also features two Dutch-inspired cafes, and the flour-grinding windmill [http://www.foxtonwindmill.co.nz/de-molen.html De Molen].\n\nThe [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Trust Dutch Connection Museum Trust] collaborated in partnership with Horowhenua District Council, and the [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre/Te-Taitoa-Maori-o-Te-Awahou-Trust Te Taitoa M\u0101ori o Te Awahou Trust] to create the Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom facility - the home of the Oranjehof Dutch Connection Centre.\n\n== An Unknown Story == \n[[File:Gepakt en gezakt - Dutch immigrant stories.jpg|thumb|Gepakt en gezakt - Dutch immigrant stories]]\nThe Dutch \u2013 and their children and grandchildren \u2013 helped to change New Zealand and transform into a more diverse, multi-cultural nation since the 1950s and 1960s<ref>https://uhcl.recollect.co.nz/nodes/view/25708</ref>. They arrived as the first big wave of non-English speaking immigrants, in what was then still a strongly British nation.\n\nDutch migrants were issued an \u2018Alien Pass\u2019 and told to become \u2018New Britishers\u2019. The directive from both Dutch and New Zealand Governments was to merge into mainstream society. It became the norm to ignore the culture of origin, and speak English at home.<ref>http://www.netherlandsfoundation.org.nz/our-stories/read-our-stories/tasman-s-legacy/</ref>\n\n=== Invisible Immigrants ===\n[[File:Abel Tasman - Arrival in 1642.jpg|thumb|Abel Tasman - Arrival in 1642]]\nAs a result, the Dutch became the \u2018Invisible Immigrants\u2019<ref>https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/the-invisible-immigrants/</ref>, as they integrated into mainstream society<ref>http://www.caddanz.org.nz/massey/fms/Research/ntom/Home-Abroad-A-Profile-of-the-Dutch-Diaspora-in-New-Zealand.pdf?D922BDB365A154782D05E8DF9E19906E</ref>. In a way, the Dutch migrants are missing from the pages of history. Michael King, in his Penguin \u2018History of New Zealand\u2019 tells the story of all migrant groups<ref>http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/docs/2004/NZJH_38_1_07.pdf</ref> \u2013 except the Dutch. Oranjehof is the place that addresses that omission. \n\nToday, at least one in every 40 or so New Zealanders has some Dutch heritage or connections<ref>http://www.caddanz.org.nz/massey/fms/Research/ntom/Home-Abroad-A-Profile-of-the-Dutch-Diaspora-in-New-Zealand.pdf?D922BDB365A154782D05E8DF9E19906E</ref>. These hard-working arrivals influenced the tastes of a nation \u2013 in the arts, dance, religion, food. Oranjehof tells those eye-opening stories in interactive ways, which include digital displays and hands-on games. \n\nThe history of the Dutch in Aotearoa goes all the way back to Tasman's arrival in 1642, some 127 years before Captain Cook<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel_Tasman</ref>.\n\n== Oranjehof Museum ==\n[[File:Kunst - Art and design.jpg|thumb|Kunst - Art and design]]\nOranjehof is a museum that is quintessential Dutch, with a colourful sense of humour of its own, plenty of gezelligheid, and a sense of clear Dutch design. \n\nDutch artists represented, include photographer [http://suite.co.nz/answestra Ans Westra], sculptor [http://www.gibbsfarm.org.nz/vandeneijkel.php Leon van den Eijkel]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_van_den_Eijkel</ref>, and ceramicists [https://www.cordys.co.nz/auctions/Z12/catalogue Anneke Borren] and [http://www.newzealandpottery.net/t3512-melis-van-der-sluis Melis van der Sluis]. Designers include [[Doris de Pont]] and [https://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/topic/886 Frank Carpay].\n\n=== Dutch Connections ===\nThe story of the Dutch in New Zealand touches on many aspects of Kiwi life<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Carpay</ref><ref>http://www.nzfashionmuseum.org.nz/doris-de-pont</ref>. The origins of Vogel\u2019s bread, Verkerks salami, and artisan Gouda and Edam cheeses are all Dutch.  Many New Zealanders have lived in a Lockwood home, or drank coffee at [https://nzhistory.govt.nz/media/photo/interior-suzy%26%23039%3Bs-coffee-bar Suzy\u2019s Coffee Lounge] \u2013 the \u2018Queen of the Coffee Houses\u2019 in Wellington<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/108528916/wellington-cafe-legend-suzy-van-der-kwast-has-died-aged-80</ref>. \n\nA \u2018touch of Dutch\u2019 can be found just about anywhere in New Zealand \u2013 even in the country\u2019s name, due to the arrival of Abel Tasman and the first European encounter with the Maori<ref>https://nzhistory.govt.nz/people/abel-tasman</ref>. \n\n== The Exhibition and Collection ==\n[[File:Zand zeep soda.jpg|thumb|Keukenspul - Dutch kitchen]]\nOranjehof preserves Dutch heritage \u2013 history, treasures, art, language, identity, culture, Nederlandse dingen.\nAs the Dutch Connection Centre, it is the centrepoint for the Dutch community in New Zealand. \n\nOranjehof showcases:\n* Tasman's travels  \u2013 The first meeting of two worlds, M\u0101ori and P\u0101keh\u0101\n* The story of why so many Nederlanders ventured to Aotearoa\n* The Dutch influence on art and design - And on coffee culture, cheese making, agriculture and dairy\n* Nederlandse Taal \u2013 You can listen to Dutch language on Dutch radio\n* Traditional games - Plus dress up costumes for selfies \n\n== De Molen Windmill ==\n[[File:Molen lights.jpg|thumb|De Molen and Te Awahou front]]\nThe full size replica of a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[windmill]], De Molen,  was completed and opened in 2003<ref>http://www.timberdesign.org.nz/journal/case-studies/demolen-a-traditional-dutch-windmill-and-shining/</ref> and underwent some major repairs in 2018<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/102784075/landmark-foxton-windmill-de-molen-to-run-again-after-repairs</ref>.  \n\nDe Molen is the result of Netherlands-New Zealand collaboration. Running gear, millstones and sails were produced and installed by Vaags Molenwerken in Aalten, the Netherlands. The mill was built largely by volunteers, under the direction of local builder Cor Slobbe.<ref>https://www.timberdesign.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/De-Molen-The-Wooden-Design-inside.pdf</ref> The 17th century design with wooden beams is impressive to behold, especially when the mill is creaking loudly and the parts are moving, as it grinds flour on windy days.\n\nThe fully working [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/stellingmolen Stellingmolen] windmill produces stone-ground [[flour]], which can be purchased inside the mill's Dutch Deli. Visitors can climb up three floors, to witness the wooden mechanical workings of the mill in action - examples of traditional Dutch 17th Century engineering. The miller sets the blades in motion on windy days, and is available for tours to explain the history of milling, or for a more casual conversation.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Oranjehof-Dutch-Connection-Centre Oranjehof Museum]\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Te-Awahou-Nieuwe-Stroom/Piriharakeke-Generation-Inspiration-Centre Piriharakeke museum]\n* [https://www.teawahou.com/Home Te Awahou Nieuwe Stroom]\n* [http://www.foxtonwindmill.co.nz/de-molen.html De Molen - In the Cultural Park]\n* [https://www.foxton.org.nz/attr-flax.html Flax Stripper Museum - In the Cultural Park]\n\n== References  ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Arjanvanderboon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oranjehof"}
{"title_page": "Accra Lions FC", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| ground = [[Accra Sports Stadium]]<br/>[[Accra]], [[Greater Accra Region|Greater Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| capacity = 40,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/gha/ohene_djan_sports_stadium|title=Accra Sports Stadium \u2013 StadiumDB.com|website=stadiumdb.com}}</ref>\n| season = [[2018 Ghanaian Division League|2018]]\n| current = <!--2018 Ghanaian Division One League-->\n| clubname = Accra Lions FC (ALFC)\n| image = Logo.jpg ALFC.jpg\n| image_size = \n| fullname = Accra Lions Football Club\n| founded = 12 December 2015<ref>{{cite web|title=Our history|url=http://www.accralions.com/club/history|publisher=Accra Lions Football Club|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n| coach = {{Flagicon|GER}} [[Rainer Kraft]]\n| league = [[Division One League, Ghana|Ghana Division One League]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Division One - Zone Three|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/division-one/division-one-zone-three|publisher=Ghana Football Association|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n| website = www.accralions.com\n| pattern_b1 = _Kit body blue.PNG\n| shorts1 = 0000FF\n | pattern_la2              =\n | pattern_b2               =\n | pattern_ra2              =\n | pattern_sh2              =\n | pattern_so2              =\n | leftarm2                 = 1845BD\n | body2                    = 1845BD\n | rightarm2                = 1845BD\n | shorts2                  = FFFFFF\n | socks2                   = 1845BD\n}}\n\n'''Accra Lions Football Club''' is a [[professional]] [[sports]] club based in [[East Legon]], [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]. The club is competing in the [[Division One League, Ghana|Division One League]], the second-tier of Ghana [[Association football|Football]] and in the [[Ghanaian FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 MTN FA Cup preliminary round fixtures|url=https://footballmadeinghana.com/2018/04/05/2018-mtn-fa-cup-preliminary-round-fixtures/|publisher=FootballMadeinGhana|accessdate=6 August 2018|date=5 April 2018}}</ref> They play their home matches at the [[Accra Sports Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Accra Lions FC opts for Accra Sports Stadium as home ground for Division One League campaign|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/accra-lions-fc-opts-for-accra-sports-stadium-as-home-ground-for-division-one-league-campaign|publisher=Ghanasoccernet|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> [[Rainer Kraft]] is the coach of the side.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Accra Lions FC.jpg|thumb|ALFC training at the Presec Park in Legon-Accra]]\n\nAccra Lions Football Club was founded on 12 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our history|url=http://www.accralions.com/club/history|publisher=Accra Lions Football Club|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThey secure promotion after just two seasons in the [[Greater Accra]] [[Division Two (Ghana)|Division Two]] after winning the Zone IV division with a record 73 points in 28 matches to qualify for the middle league.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|url=http://www.accralions.com/club/history|publisher=Accra Lions FC|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Greater Accra]] promotional playoffs at the [[Tema Sports Stadium]], Accra Lions booked the sole qualification ticket with a 100% winning record. They beat Emmanuel FC (4-1), R-Stakes (3-0) and Photizo Future Professionals (2-0) to slot into Division One Zone III which includes clubs based in [[Greater Accra]], [[Eastern Region (Ghana)|Eastern Region]] and [[Volta Region]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Accra Lions FC snatch Greater Accra Division One League ticket with three straight wins|url=http://ghanasoccernet.com/accra-lions-fc-snatch-greater-accra-division-one-league-ticket-with-three-straight-wins|publisher=GhanaSoccernet|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2018, Accra Lions officially announced the [[Accra Sports Stadium]] as their new home ground for the 2017/2018 Division One League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Accra Lions FC opts for Accra Sports Stadium as home ground for Division One League campaign|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/accra-lions-fc-opts-for-accra-sports-stadium-as-home-ground-for-division-one-league-campaign|publisher=Ghanasoccernet|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 they made their debut in the [[Division One League, Ghana|Ghana Division One]]- Zone Three<ref>{{cite web|title=Division One - Zone Three|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/division-one/division-one-zone-three|publisher=Ghana Football Association|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref> and in the [[Ghanaian FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MTN FA CUP PRELIMINARY ROUND GAMES TO BE PLAYED THIS WEEKEND|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/mtn-fa-cup-preliminary-round-games-to-be-played-this-weekend|publisher=Ghana Football Association|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Staff ==\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Accra Lions FC Staff|url=http://www.accralions.com/team/staff|publisher=Accra Lions Football Club|accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n;Head coach\n* {{Flagicon|Germany}} [[Rainer Kraft]]\n\n;Team Manager:\n* {{Flagicon|Ghana}} Ishmael Hamidu\n\n;Director of Finance & Administration\n\n* {{Flagicon|Ghana}} Enoch Kofi Osei\n\n;Assistant Coach:\n* {{Flagicon|Ghana}} Nuru Yakubu\n\n;Goalkeeper's coach:\n* {{Flagicon|Ghana}} Osei Boateng\n\n;Physiotherapist:\n* {{Flagicon|Ghana}} Manaf Abubakar\n\n;Head of Scouting:\n* {{Flagicon|USA}} Paul Goodrich\n\n== Current squad ==\n[[File:Champions .jpg|thumb|Accra Lions FC are champions]]\n''As of 1 February 2020''<ref>{{cite web|title=Accra Lions FC Squad|url=http://www.accralions.com/team|publisher=Accra Lions Football Club|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:50%;\"\n|-\n! No.\n! Nat.\n! Name\n! Date of Birth\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#1845BD\"| Keepers\n|-\n| 1 || {{Flagicon|Ghana}} ||style=\"text-align:left;\"|[http://www.accralions.com/team/detail/5b184f2b2ecf9d63cf60e5e7 Michael Abraham] || 30.12.2003\n|-\n| 22 || {{Flagicon|Ghana}} ||style=\"text-alig